This paper is likely to belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) category as it discusses the implementation of a Random Feature Extractor (RFE) core as the first stage of an Extreme Learning Machine (ELM), which is a type of neural network. Additionally, the paper focuses on achieving high accuracy on the MNIST database of handwritten digits, which is a common benchmark dataset for evaluating neural network performance. 

The paper is also likely to belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) category as it specifically applies the RFE core to image recognition tasks. 

The paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) category as it discusses the use of weight reuse techniques and avoiding computation cost in the implementation of the RFE core. 

The paper could potentially belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) category as the low-power mixed signal ASIC discussed in the paper could be used as a co-processor in portable electronic gadgets with cameras, which could have applications in robotics. 

Finally, the paper may belong to the Emerging Technologies (cs.ET) category as it discusses the implementation of a low-power mixed signal ASIC, which is a type of emerging technology.
